    "story": {
      "content": "Day 4, afternoon meditation. Rachel was monitoring the Blue section when she saw it.\n\nRow 12, seat 7. A man‚Äîmid-40s‚Äîsuddenly went rigid. His whole body stiffened. Then jerking. Rhythmic, involuntary movements. His eyes rolled back.\n\nRachel's training kicked in immediately.\n\nSeizure.\n\nShe moved quickly to him. Checked: breathing? Yes. Space around him? Clear. Nothing sharp nearby? No.\n\nShe signaled another volunteer: 'Get Medical. NOW.'\n\nShe knelt beside him. Didn't touch him. Didn't try to hold him down. Didn't put anything in his mouth. Just watched. Timed it. Protected his space.\n\n45 seconds. The jerking slowed. Stopped. His body relaxed.\n\nMedical arrived within 90 seconds of her signal. Two RNs, equipment ready.\n\nRachel briefed them quickly: 'Tonic-clonic seizure. Lasted about 45 seconds. Stopped on its own. He's breathing. Post-ictal now.'\n\nThe lead RN looked at her. 'You did everything right. Perfect response. Timing the seizure, protecting his space, not intervening incorrectly, getting us here fast. This is textbook.'\n\nThe man came to slowly. Confused. Disoriented. Medical assessed him, checked vitals, took history. Turned out: known epilepsy. Forgot his medication that morning.\n\nMedical monitored him for 30 minutes. He was fine. Chose to continue the event with increased medication compliance.\n\nAfter the event, Rachel's Team Lead pulled her aside.\n\n'You handled that seizure like a pro. Do you know why it mattered that you did it right?'\n\n'Because I didn't make it worse?'\n\n'Exactly. People panic. They try to hold the person down, put things in their mouth, move them during the seizure. That causes injury. You did none of that. You protected him by knowing what NOT to do. That's the difference between a good volunteer and a great one.'\n\nRachel understood: knowing the protocol isn't just about helping. It's about not harming."
    },
    "whyThisMatters": {
      "quote": "The body has an innate intelligence. Sometimes our job is simply to protect it while it does what it needs to do.",
      "author": "Dr. Joe Dispenza",
      "content": "Seizures happen at these events. Not often, but they happen.\n\nWhy?\n\n1. **Pre-existing conditions:** People with epilepsy attend. Sometimes they forget medications. Sometimes stress or lack of sleep lowers their threshold.\n\n2. **Intense meditation states:** Deep breathing, altered states, hyperventilation‚Äîthese can occasionally trigger seizure activity in susceptible individuals.\n\n3. **Dehydration and exhaustion:** Long days, inadequate water, low blood sugar‚Äîthese are seizure triggers.\n\n4. **Unknown conditions:** Some people have their first seizure at an event. No prior history. This is rare but possible.\n\nYou will likely witness a seizure if you volunteer enough times. When you do, your response matters.\n\n**Good response:**\n- Prevents injury\n- Gets appropriate medical help\n- Provides accurate information to Medical\n- Stays calm, models calm for others\n- Allows seizure to run its course safely\n\n**Poor response:**\n- Causes injury (restraining, inserting objects in mouth)\n- Delays medical help (panic, confusion, unclear communication)\n- Provides inaccurate information (guessing vs. observing)\n- Creates chaos (yelling, panicking, drawing crowd)\n- Interferes with the body's process\n\nThis chapter teaches you:\n‚Ä¢ How to recognize different types of seizures\n‚Ä¢ The exact protocol for responding to tonic-clonic (grand mal) seizures\n‚Ä¢ What NEVER to do (dangerous myths)\n‚Ä¢ When to call 911 vs. when Medical handles it\n‚Ä¢ Post-seizure care and monitoring\n‚Ä¢ How to document and communicate what you witnessed\n\nThis is life-saving information. Not theoretical. Practical. Precise.\n\nYou're learning to respond with calm competence when seconds matter.\n\nPay attention to every word."
    },
