      {
        "title": "Types of Seizures: What They Look Like",
        "content": "**Not all seizures look the same. Recognition is the first step.**\n\n**TONIC-CLONIC SEIZURE (Grand Mal) - MOST DRAMATIC:**\n\n**What you see:**. Sudden loss of consciousness‚Äîperson falls if standing. Body goes rigid and stiff (tonic phase) - 10-20 seconds. Then rhythmic jerking movements (clonic phase) - 1-3 minutes. Eyes may roll back or be open but unseeing. Jaw may clench. May bite tongue or inside of cheek. May lose bladder/bowel control. May make sounds (moaning, grunting) but is not conscious. Breathing may be irregular during seizure. Skin may look bluish (cyanosis) briefly due to breathing pause\n\n**After seizure stops:**. Person is unresponsive or very confused (post-ictal state). May be sleepy, disoriented, aggressive, or frightened. Gradually returns to awareness over 5-30 minutes. May have headache, muscle soreness, fatigue. Usually no memory of the seizure itself\n\n**FOCAL (PARTIAL) SEIZURE - MORE SUBTLE:**\n\n**What you see:**. Person may remain conscious but seem 'off'. Staring blankly, unresponsive to questions. Repetitive movements: lip smacking, hand movements, picking at clothes. May wander or seem confused. Speech may be garbled or absent. Lasts 1-2 minutes typically. Person slowly returns to normal afterward. May not remember the episode\n\n**ABSENCE SEIZURE - VERY BRIEF:**\n\n**What you see:**. Sudden blank stare. Brief pause in activity (5-10 seconds). Eyes may flutter or roll up slightly. Returns to normal immediately after. May not realize they had a seizure. More common in children but can occur in adults\n\n**MYOCLONIC SEIZURE - QUICK JERKS:**\n\n**What you see:**. Sudden brief jerks or twitches. May affect one limb or whole body. Person remains conscious. May drop things or fall. Very brief‚Äîa second or less\n\n**The one you're most likely to encounter and need to respond to: TONIC-CLONIC.**\n\nThe rest of this chapter focuses on that type‚Äîthe most dramatic and the one requiring the clearest protocol."
      },
      {
        "title": "The Protocol: Exact Steps for Tonic-Clonic Seizure Response",
        "content": "**When you recognize a tonic-clonic seizure, follow this protocol EXACTLY:**\n\n**STEP 1: STAY CALM AND ASSESS (5 seconds)**. Confirm it's a seizure (loss of consciousness, rhythmic jerking). Note the time it started (check watch/phone). Quick safety scan: Are they about to fall off something? Hit something sharp?\n\n**STEP 2: PROTECT FROM INJURY (Immediate)**. If they're falling, try to ease them to the ground if possible. If already on ground, ensure space around them. Move furniture, equipment, or other objects that could cause injury. Do NOT try to hold them down or stop the movements. Do NOT put anything in their mouth. Do NOT try to move them unless they're in immediate danger (fire, stairs, etc.)\n\n**STEP 3: GET HELP (Immediate‚Äîwhile protecting them)**. Signal another volunteer or staff member. Say clearly: 'Medical emergency‚Äîseizure. Get Medical NOW.'. If you have phone, post in Telegram:\n  'üö®üö® MEDICAL EMERGENCY\n  ‚Ä¢ [Name if known]\n  ‚Ä¢ SEIZURE IN PROGRESS\n  ‚Ä¢ Location: [precise location]\n  ‚Ä¢ Started at [time]\n  ‚Ä¢ I am with them'. Do NOT leave them alone to find help‚Äîsend someone else\n\n**STEP 4: MONITOR AND TIME (During seizure)**. Stay with them, position yourself nearby. Keep timing‚Äînote how long the seizure lasts. Observe their breathing (may be irregular‚Äîthis is normal during seizure). Watch for injury (hitting head, biting tongue, etc.). Keep others back‚Äîprotect their dignity and give Medical space when they arrive. Do NOT restrain them or put pressure on their limbs\n\n**STEP 5: POSITION FOR SAFETY (When jerking stops)**. Once jerking completely stops and body relaxes, check breathing. If breathing normally and no neck/spinal injury suspected: Turn them on their side (recovery position)\n  - This prevents choking if they vomit\n  - Keeps airway clear\n  - Tilt head slightly back to open airway. If NOT breathing or breathing very poorly: DO NOT MOVE‚ÄîMedical will handle airway. If neck/spinal injury suspected (fell from height, hit head hard): DO NOT MOVE‚ÄîMedical will handle\n\n**STEP 6: PROVIDE POST-ICTAL CARE (After seizure, before Medical arrives)**. Talk to them calmly: 'You're safe. You had a seizure. Help is coming.'. Don't expect them to respond coherently yet. Keep them on their side. Loosen any tight clothing around neck. Stay with them, provide calm presence. Don't give them food, water, or medication. Don't let them walk around (they're disoriented, may fall)\n\n**STEP 7: BRIEF MEDICAL (When they arrive)**. How long the seizure lasted (total time from start to stop of jerking). Description of what you saw. Any injuries (hit head, bit tongue, etc.). Are they breathing normally now. Level of consciousness post-seizure. Any information about them (name, known epilepsy, etc.)\n\n**CRITICAL TIMING THRESHOLDS:**. Seizure lasting MORE than 5 minutes ‚Üí Call 911 immediately (Status epilepticus‚Äîlife threatening). Second seizure before they fully recover from first ‚Üí Call 911 immediately. Not breathing normally after seizure stops ‚Üí Call 911 immediately. Injured in the fall (head trauma, broken bones) ‚Üí Medical assesses, may call 911",
        "pullQuote": {
          "text": "In an emergency, the body knows what to do. Our job is to create safety for its intelligence to work.",
          "author": "Dr. Joe Dispenza"
        }
      },
      {
        "title": "CRITICAL: What NEVER to Do During a Seizure",
        "content": "**These are dangerous myths that cause harm. NEVER do these:**\n\n**‚ùå NEVER put anything in their mouth**\n\n*The myth:* They'll swallow their tongue.\n*The truth:* It's physically impossible to swallow your tongue.\n*The danger:* Objects in the mouth can:\n  - Break teeth\n  - Cause choking\n  - Obstruct airway\n  - Injure your fingers if they bite down\n  - Block Medical's airway management\n\nAbsolutely nothing goes in their mouth during or immediately after a seizure. Nothing.\n\n**‚ùå NEVER try to hold them down or restrain their movements**\n\n*The myth:* You need to stop the jerking.\n*The truth:* The seizure must run its course. You can't stop it.\n*The danger:* Restraining can:\n  - Cause muscle, ligament, or bone injuries\n  - Increase their distress\n  - Injure you if they're strong\n  - Doesn't stop the seizure, just adds harm\n\nLet the body move. Protect from injury, but don't restrain.\n\n**‚ùå NEVER give them water, food, or medication during or immediately after**\n\n*The myth:* They need water or their medication.\n*The truth:* They can't swallow safely while seizing or immediately post-ictal.\n*The danger:* They can:\n  - Choke\n  - Aspirate liquid into lungs (pneumonia)\n  - Worsen medical condition\n\nWait until they're fully alert and Medical clears them to drink/eat.\n\n**‚ùå NEVER move them unless they're in immediate danger**\n\n*The myth:* They need to be more comfortable.\n*The truth:* Movement can cause injury if they have fractures or head trauma.\n*The danger:* Moving can:\n  - Worsen spinal injuries\n  - Cause additional trauma\n  - Complicate medical assessment\n\nOnly move if they're in immediate danger (fire, about to fall off something, in water). Otherwise, let them be where they are.\n\n**‚ùå NEVER leave them alone**\n\n*The myth:* They need privacy.\n*The truth:* They need monitoring in case complications arise.\n*The danger:* They could:\n  - Have another seizure\n  - Stop breathing\n  - Aspirate vomit\n  - Be confused and wander into danger\n  - Need immediate intervention\n\nStay with them until Medical arrives and takes over.\n\n**‚ùå NEVER assume they're okay immediately after**\n\n*The myth:* Seizure's over, they're fine now.\n*The truth:* Post-ictal state can last 30+ minutes. They need medical evaluation.\n*The danger:* Complications can include:\n  - Another seizure\n  - Head injury from fall\n  - Cardiac issues\n  - Underlying cause needs assessment\n\nAlways get Medical involved. Every seizure gets evaluated.\n\n**The principle: First, do no harm.**\n\nYour job during a seizure:\n1. Protect them from injury\n2. Time it\n3. Get Medical\n4. Monitor\n5. Stay calm\n\nThat's it. Everything else is either unnecessary or dangerous."
