      {
        "title": "When to Call 911: Decision Tree",
        "content": "**The Medical team usually handles seizures. But sometimes 911 is needed.**\n\n**CALL 911 IMMEDIATELY IF:**\n\n**1. Seizure lasts longer than 5 minutes**. This is status epilepticus‚Äîmedical emergency. Brain can be damaged by prolonged seizure. Medical will call 911 if they're not already there. If Medical hasn't arrived by 5-minute mark, call 911 yourself\n\n**2. Second seizure before they fully recover from first**. Called 'cluster seizures'. Indicates lack of control. Needs emergency intervention. Call 911 even if Medical is there‚Äîthey'll coordinate\n\n**3. Seizure occurred in water**. Risk of drowning. Even if they're out of water, they may have aspirated. Needs emergency evaluation. Call 911 immediately\n\n**4. Person is injured in the fall**. Head trauma. Suspected spinal injury. Broken bones. Heavy bleeding. Medical will assess and call 911 if needed, but if Medical isn't there quickly, call\n\n**5. Person is not breathing normally after seizure stops**. Breathing should resume within 1-2 minutes after seizure ends. If not breathing or breathing very poorly ‚Üí 911 immediately. Start CPR if trained and no pulse. Medical will take over when they arrive\n\n**6. First-time seizure (no history of epilepsy)**. Needs emergency evaluation to determine cause. Could be stroke, tumor, infection, or other serious condition. Medical will likely call 911 for transport. First seizure ever = emergency room\n\n**7. Person is pregnant**. Seizures during pregnancy are high risk. Needs immediate emergency care. Call 911 even if seizure is brief. Medical will coordinate but 911 should be en route\n\n**8. Person is diabetic**. Seizure could be from hypoglycemia (low blood sugar). Needs immediate glucose management. Medical handles this but may call 911 for transport. Time is critical with diabetic seizures\n\n**LET MEDICAL HANDLE (Don't call 911 yourself):**\n\n. Known epilepsy, seizure less than 5 minutes, breathing resumes normally. Person returns to baseline within expected timeframe. No injuries from fall. Medical team is present and assessing. Person declines 911 after Medical evaluation (if conscious and competent)\n\n**Your role:**\n\nProvide information to Medical so they can decide about 911. You don't have to know all the medical details‚Äîjust observe and report what you see.\n\nIf Medical hasn't arrived and it's been 5+ minutes of active seizing, or person isn't breathing post-seizure, you call 911. Don't wait.\n\n**The 911 call:**\n\n'We have a person having a seizure at [address]. The seizure has lasted [X] minutes. They are [breathing/not breathing]. We have medical personnel en route. We need an ambulance immediately.'\n\nClear. Factual. Location. Status. Done."
