      {
        "title": "Post-Seizure Care: The Recovery Phase",
        "content": "**After the seizure stops, a new phase begins: post-ictal state.**\n\n**What 'post-ictal' means:**\n\nThe period after a seizure when the brain is recovering. The person is not fully conscious or oriented. This is normal and expected. It can last 5-30 minutes, sometimes longer.\n\n**What you'll observe:**. Confusion (they don't know where they are, what happened). Disorientation (may not know the date, their name, why they're there). Sleepiness or exhaustion. Possible agitation or aggression (not personal‚Äîbrain is confused). Headache, muscle soreness. Slurred speech. Memory gaps. Emotional (crying, fear, embarrassment)\n\n**Your role during post-ictal phase:**\n\n**1. Maintain safety positioning**. Keep them on their side (recovery position). Support their head with something soft if available. Don't let them try to stand up or walk yet. They may insist they're fine‚Äîthey're not yet\n\n**2. Provide calm reassurance**. Speak softly and simply: 'You're safe. You had a seizure. You're going to be okay.'. Repeat as needed‚Äîthey may not remember you saying it. Don't ask complex questions or expect coherent answers yet. Just presence, not conversation\n\n**3. Protect dignity**. Keep onlookers back. Cover them with a blanket if clothing is displaced. Don't allow photos or videos. Treat them with respect‚Äîthey're vulnerable\n\n**4. Monitor for complications**. Watch breathing‚Äîshould be regular now. Check for injuries you might have missed. Note if they're slowly improving or staying very altered. If they have another seizure, note timing and get Medical attention immediately\n\n**5. Don't give them anything**. No water (choking risk until fully alert). No food. No medication (even if they ask for their seizure meds‚ÄîMedical decides). Wait for Medical to clear them\n\n**6. Stay with them**. Until Medical arrives. Until they're fully alert and oriented. Until someone else takes over their care. They should not be alone in this state\n\n**When Medical arrives, report:**. Total duration of seizure. Description of seizure activity. Time seizure ended. Current level of consciousness. Any injuries observed. Person's medical history if you know it (do they have epilepsy, did they mention medications, etc.). How they're doing now compared to right after seizure ended (improving, same, worse)\n\n**What Medical will do:**. Assess vital signs (pulse, blood pressure, oxygen). Check for injuries. Determine if they need hospital evaluation. If known epilepsy and typical seizure, may allow them to rest and continue event. If first-time seizure or atypical presentation, will likely arrange transport to ER. Make sure they're oriented before leaving them. Arrange for someone to stay with them\n\n**Your job ends when:**\n\nMedical says 'We've got it from here. Thank you.' Then you return to your post, ground yourself, and continue serving."
      },
      {
        "title": "Documentation and Communication",
        "content": "**After a seizure, clear documentation matters for the person's ongoing care.**\n\n**What to document (write it down immediately):**\n\n**Timing:**. What time the seizure started (be as precise as possible). What time the seizure stopped (when jerking ended). Total duration. Current time when Medical took over\n\n**Description:**. What you saw: 'Sudden loss of consciousness, fell to ground, body went rigid for approximately 15 seconds, then rhythmic jerking of all limbs for approximately 2 minutes'. Not interpretations: Just facts. Any sounds they made. Eye position if you noticed. Color of skin (normal, pale, bluish)\n\n**Injuries:**. Hit head when falling? On what?. Bit tongue or cheek? (you'll see blood). Any other visible injuries\n\n**Context:**. What were they doing when it started (sitting, standing, meditating). Any warning signs they mentioned beforehand. Had they said they weren't feeling well\n\n**Post-seizure:**. How long until they started to become responsive. Any repeated seizures. How they are when Medical takes over\n\n**What to tell Medical:**\n\nEverything above, clearly and concisely. Start with the most critical:\n\n'Tonic-clonic seizure, lasted approximately 2 minutes, started at 3:42 PM, stopped at 3:44 PM. They hit their head on the floor when they fell. Breathing resumed normally after seizure ended. They're post-ictal now, confused but breathing is fine.'\n\nThen answer any questions they have.\n\n**What to tell your Team Lead:**. That there was a seizure. That Medical was called and handled it. General outcome (person is okay, person was transported to hospital, etc.). Don't share identifying details with other volunteers‚Äîrespect privacy\n\n**What NOT to do:**. Don't post about it on social media. Don't discuss details with other participants. Don't gossip about who it was or what they looked like. Don't speculate about why it happened. This person's medical event is private\n\n**Why documentation matters:**. Medical team needs accurate information for assessment. If person goes to hospital, your observations help doctors. If there are questions later, your written notes are reliable. You'll forget details quickly‚Äîwrite them immediately\n\n**Keep it simple:**\n\nSmall notebook, note the time, duration, what you saw. That's enough. Medical will ask for more details if needed."
      }
